In this demonstration, we show how the KBase iPython notebook can be used to explore seqeunce quality information.

x

We'll look at three example samples:

One exhibits good quality ("qc_good")

Another exhibits poor quality ("qc_poor")

A third demonstrates how artifacts like adaptor contamination can be detetected ("qc_ugly").

We start by initializing the notebook:

In [1]:
init_ipy()
init_ipy()
. . .
x

Then we download precomputed QC data for three metagenomic sequence samples:

In [2]:
qc_set  = get_collection(mgids=['mgm4440640.3','mgm4473069.3','mgm4473205.3'])
qc_good = QC(metagenome=qc_set.metagenomes['mgm4440640.3'])
qc_bad  = QC(metagenome=qc_set.metagenomes['mgm4473069.3'])
qc_ugly = QC(metagenome=qc_set.metagenomes['mgm4473205.3'])

We can get an intial assessment of the samples by looking at their DRISEE (PMID 22685393) errors:

In [3]:
print "good : ",qc_good.drisee.summary['data'][6]
print "bad  : ", qc_bad.drisee.summary['data'][6]
print "ugly : ", qc_ugly.drisee.summary['data'][6]
good :  0.189
bad  :  44.776
ugly :  34.196

x

We can get a much more detailed picture of the DRISEE error by looking at the full DRISEE error profiles:

In [4]:
qc_good.drisee.plot(title='good drisee')
qc_bad.drisee.plot(title='bad drisee')
qc_ugly.drisee.plot(title='ugly drisee')
. . .
x

We can also look at the nucletide profiles for these data sets:

In [5]:
qc_good.bp_histo.plot(title='good bp histogram')
qc_bad.bp_histo.plot(title='bad bp histogram')
qc_ugly.bp_histo.plot(title='ugly bp histogram')
. . .
x

The DRISEE and nucleotide profiles lead to similar conclusions, the good sample exhibits reasonable seqeunce quality, and a random distribution of bases (25% A,T,C, & G), as we would expect for most community data. The low quality and "ugly" samples both contain a substantial amount of adaptor contamination, (apparant as biased dsitributions of A,T,C,& G) in the nucleotide profiles. These samples also exhibit poor DRISEE errors.

x

The kmer spectra reveal additional information about the samples:

Kmer spectra permit us to rapidly identify sequence diversity and coverage ranges for sequence datasets. This knowledge can inform samplecomparison and exploitation via clustering and assembly.

The kmer.plot_abundance method gives us graphical summaries of kmer abundance and diversity, plotting the logarithm of the kmer abundance against the logarithm of kmer rank.

In [6]:
qc_good.kmer.plot_abundance(title='good kmer spectra')
qc_good.kmer.plot_abundance(title='good kmer spectra')
. . .
x

The kmer abundance graph from good shows us that the sequences represented are diverse. None of the biological seqeunces have coverages over 100x; most of the sequence is approx 10x, and sequencing adapters occur at 1000x.

In [7]:
qc_ugly.kmer.plot_abundance(title='ugly kmer spectra')
qc_ugly.kmer.plot_abundance(title='ugly kmer spectra')
. . .
x

The abundance graph for ugly, by contrast, shows an adapter abundance of almost 100,000x. These artifactual sequences consume about a third of the sequencing yield and have unknown consequences on downstream annotation.

x

args = qc_set.rarefaction.plot(arg_list=True)
for s in args['data']['series']:
    s['name'] = qc_names[s['name'].split()[0]]
Ipy.RETINA.plot(**args)
